{"sections":[{"chapter":"Tutorials","kind":"hero","title":"Create a simple Scope","estimatedTimeInMinutes":20,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Define a scope object with state member variables representing","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"a part of your app’s status, define the events that may affect"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"this state, and create a view to display the state."}]}]},{"kind":"tasks","tasks":[{"anchor":"Create-a-scope","contentSection":[{"kind":"contentAndMedia","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Scopes in Statoscope represent self-contained sections of your app’s logic, managing state and reacting to user or system-driven events. Each scope contains its own member variables to track state, an "},{"code":"update","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" function to handle the defined events (called "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"When"},{"type":"text","text":" cases), and can communicate with views or other components."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A simple use case is a counter, where we want to display the count value and allow the user to increment or decrement it by tapping buttons."}]}],"mediaPosition":"trailing"}],"title":"Create a scope","stepsSection":[{"type":"step","runtimePreview":null,"code":"01-01-01-code-0001.swift","caption":[],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Create a file "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Counter.swift"},{"text":" and import the Statoscope library. This is the first step towards creating your counter scope.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"Statoscope helps in defining your app’s state as a separate, modular component that can easily be tested.","type":"text"}]}],"media":null},{"type":"step","code":"01-01-01-code-0002.swift","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Define your state using member variables.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We suggest using clear, sentence-like naming for state variables. This will make your code more readable and also simplify acceptance testing."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"code":"01-01-01-code-0003.swift","runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Add the "},{"code":"When","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" events that can occur in your scope."}]}],"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"code":"When","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" cases represent the events that trigger state changes. Again, using sentence-like names for these events ensures that your code is both readable and self-explanatory in tests."}]}],"type":"step","media":null},{"media":null,"code":"01-01-01-code-0004.swift","runtimePreview":null,"type":"step","caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This method will be responsible for managing how your state evolves when events occur. For now, leave the method skeleton in place — we’ll return to it later."}]}],"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Finally, define the ","type":"text"},{"code":"update","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" method that will contain your business logic."}]}]},{"code":"01-01-01-code-0005.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Before building the real scope implementation via the "},{"code":"update","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" method,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"let’s take a look at how we can write acceptance tests for the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"current state’s scope."}]}],"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"One of the main goals of the Statoscope architecture is to achieve"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"ACCEPTANCE AS CODE"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":". This means your tests will closely align with the user’s acceptance criteria, making the testing process more intuitive and reflective of real user scenarios.","type":"text"}]}],"media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"type":"step"},{"runtimePreview":null,"media":null,"caption":[],"type":"step","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can try running the test now, but it will fail until we implement"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the actual logic in the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"update"},{"text":" method.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"code":"01-01-01-code-0004.swift"},{"caption":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For this counter example, the logic involves updating the count when the user taps either the increment or decrement button, ensuring that the count never drops below zero."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"step","media":null,"code":"01-01-01-code-0006.swift","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Now it’s time to implement the "},{"code":"update","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" method, which contains the state maintenance and business logic of your app’s scope.","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"code":"01-01-01-code-0007.swift","runtimePreview":null,"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"We will soon create a view to display the state. Since we’ll be","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"using SwiftUI, adopt the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ObservableObject"},{"type":"text","text":" protocol and use "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Published"},{"type":"text","text":""},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for the state variables that the view will observe and reflect."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"step","caption":[],"media":null}]},{"anchor":"Create-your-view","contentSection":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Now that we’ve set up the scope, it’s time to build the view that will interact with this state. Using SwiftUI, we will create a simple view that displays the current count and provides buttons to increment or decrement the value. This will allow the user to interact with the scope’s state.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The view will automatically update when the state changes, thanks to the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ObservableObject"},{"text":" protocol and ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Published","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" properties.","type":"text"}]}],"mediaPosition":"trailing","kind":"contentAndMedia"}],"title":"Create your view","stepsSection":[{"runtimePreview":null,"code":"01-01-01-code-0008.swift","media":null,"caption":[],"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Let’s create our view. SwiftUI’s declarative syntax will help you define this easily and make your source code straightforward."}]}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"So far so good, we’ve built our first scope implementing a simple counter. The scope manages the state, the view displays it, and the user interacts with the scope through the UI."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Move to the next chapters to understand ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Effects"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":" and ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Scope composition","type":"text"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":", where we’ll expand the functionality and connect multiple scopes together for more complex app features."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"action":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects","overridingTitle":"Get started","type":"reference","isActive":true,"overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"text":"Get started","type":"text"}]},"title":"State, When and Effects","kind":"callToAction","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Trigger effects that will get back to your scope as a new When event."}],"featuredEyebrow":"Tutorial"}],"metadata":{"role":"project","title":"Create a simple Scope","categoryPathComponent":"StatoscopeTutorial","category":"Statoscope Architecture"},"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"major":0,"minor":3},"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-01-StateAndWhen"},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/StatoscopeTutorial","doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/StatoscopeTutorial\/$volume","doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/StatoscopeTutorial\/Tutorials"]],"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/StatoscopeTutorial","modules":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/StatoscopeTutorial\/Tutorials","projects":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-01-StateAndWhen","sections":[{"kind":"task","reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-01-StateAndWhen#Create-a-scope"},{"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-01-StateAndWhen#Create-your-view","kind":"task"}]},{"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects","sections":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects#What-is-a-side-effect","kind":"task"},{"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects#Typed-effects","kind":"task"}]},{"sections":[{"kind":"task","reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-03-Middleware#Logging-middleware"},{"kind":"task","reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-03-Middleware#Built-in-Library-logging"}],"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-03-Middleware"},{"sections":[{"kind":"task","reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-04-Injection#Designing-a-Dependency"}],"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-04-Injection"},{"reference":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-05-Scopes","sections":[{"k