n","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-03-Middleware#Logging-middleware","type":"section","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-03-middleware#Logging-middleware","role":"pseudoSymbol"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-05-Scopes#Design-scopes":{"role":"pseudoSymbol","abstract":[{"text":"Defining all state and When events in a single Statostore doesn’t scale. We need to decide where exactly to split our state and events into separate state parts or Scopes. Sometimes separation is obvious and sometimes developers want to separate state and events that are inevitably coupled due to the nature of the business logic. However, this article will focus in how to separate the state of our apps in different scopes.","type":"text"}],"kind":"section","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-05-Scopes#Design-scopes","type":"section","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-05-scopes#Design-scopes","title":"Design scopes"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-03-Middleware#Built-in-Library-logging":{"title":"Built-in Library logging","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Understand how the single entry point enables pretty interesting features"}],"kind":"section","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-03-Middleware#Built-in-Library-logging","type":"section","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-03-middleware#Built-in-Library-logging","role":"pseudoSymbol"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-03-Middleware":{"role":"project","abstract":[{"text":"Understand how the single entry point enables pretty interesting features","type":"text"}],"kind":"project","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-03-Middleware","type":"topic","estimatedTime":"30min","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-03-middleware","title":"Single entry point and\/or middlewares"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-01-StateAndWhen#Create-a-scope":{"role":"pseudoSymbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Define a scope object with state member variables representing"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"a part of your app’s status, define the events that may affect","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"this state, and create a view to display the state.","type":"text"}],"kind":"section","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-01-StateAndWhen#Create-a-scope","type":"section","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-01-stateandwhen#Create-a-scope","title":"Create a scope"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/StatoscopeTutorial/Tutorials":{"title":"Tutorials","abstract":[],"kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/StatoscopeTutorial\/Tutorials","type":"topic","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscopetutorial\/tutorials","role":"article"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-04-Injection#Designing-a-Dependency":{"title":"Designing a Dependency","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn how to easily design dependencies and inject them into your scopes. Dependency injection simplifies the structure of your code by externalizing the management of dependencies, making your code more modular, testable, and flexible. In this tutorial, we will demonstrate dependency injection using an example of a simple news feed application."}],"kind":"section","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-04-Injection#Designing-a-Dependency","type":"section","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-04-injection#Designing-a-Dependency","role":"pseudoSymbol"},"01-01-01-code-0008.swift":{"type":"file","content":["import Statoscope","import SwiftUI","","private struct CounterView: View {","    @StateObject var model = Counter()","    var body: some View {","        VStack {","            Text(\"\\(model.viewDisplaysTotalCount)\")","            HStack {","                Button(\"+\") {","                    model.send(.userTappedIncrementButton)","                }","                Button(\"-\") {","                    model.send(.userTappedDecrementButton)","                }","            }","        }","    }","}"],"identifier":"01-01-01-code-0008.swift","fileType":"swift","fileName":"CounterView.swift","syntax":"swift","highlights":[]},"01-01-01-code-0006.swift":{"type":"file","identifier":"01-01-01-code-0006.swift","content":["import Statoscope","","private final class Counter: Scope {","","    var viewDisplaysTotalCount: Int = 0","","    enum When {","        case userTappedIncrementButton","        case userTappedDecrementButton","    }","","    func update(_ when: When) throws {","        switch when {","        case .userTappedIncrementButton:","            viewDisplaysTotalCount += 1","        case .userTappedDecrementButton:","            viewDisplaysTotalCount = max(0, viewDisplaysTotalCount - 1)","        }","    }","}"],"fileType":"swift","syntax":"swift","fileName":"Counter.swift","highlights":[{"line":13},{"line":14},{"line":15},{"line":16},{"line":17},{"line":18}]},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-01-StateAndWhen":{"title":"Create a simple Scope","estimatedTime":"20min","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Define a scope object with state member variables representing"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"a part of your app’s status, define the events that may affect","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"this state, and create a view to display the state."}],"kind":"project","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-01-StateAndWhen","type":"topic","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-01-stateandwhen","role":"project"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-01-StateAndWhen#Create-your-view":{"title":"Create your view","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Define a scope object with state member variables representing"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"a part of your app’s status, define the events that may affect","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"this state, and create a view to display the state."}],"kind":"section","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-01-StateAndWhen#Create-your-view","type":"section","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-01-stateandwhen#Create-your-view","role":"pseudoSymbol"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects":{"role":"project","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects","estimatedTime":"30min","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-02-statewhenandeffects","type":"topic","title":"State, When and Effects","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Trigger effects that will get back to your scope as a new When event."}],"kind":"project"},"01-01-01-code-0007.swift":{"type":"file","content":["import Statoscope","","private final class Counter: Scope, ObservableObject {","","    @Published var viewDisplaysTotalCount: Int = 0","","    enum When {","        case userTappedIncrementButton","        case userTappedDecrementButton","    }","","    func update(_ when: When) throws {","        switch when {","        case .userTappedIncrementButton:","            viewDisplaysTotalCount += 1","        case .userTappedDecrementButton:","            viewDisplaysTotalCount = max(0, viewDisplaysTotalCount - 1)","        }","    }","}"],"identifier":"01-01-01-code-0007.swift","fileType":"swift","fileName":"Counter.swift","syntax":"swift","highlights":[{"line":3},{"line":5}]},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-05-Scopes":{"role":"project","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-05-Scopes","estimatedTime":"30min","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-05-scopes","type":"topic","title":"Scopes","abstract":[{"text":"Defining all state and When events in a single Statostore doesn’t scale. We need to decide where exactly to split our state and events into separate state parts or Scopes. Sometimes separation is obvious and sometimes developers want to separate state and events that are inevitably coupled due to the nature of the business logic. However, this article will focus in how to separate the state of our apps in different scopes.","type":"text"}],"kind":"project"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-05-Scopes#Views-and-scopes":{"role":"pseudoSymbol","abstract":[{"text":"Defining all state and When events in a single Statostore doesn’t scale. We need to decide where exactly to split our state and events into separate state parts or Scopes. Sometimes separation is obvious and sometimes developers want to separate state and events that are inevitably coupled due to the nature of the business logic. However, this article will focus in how to separate the state of our apps in different scopes.","type":"text"}],"kind":"section","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-05-Scopes#Views-and-scopes","type":"section","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-05-scopes#Views-and-scopes","title":"Views and scopes"},"01-01-01-code-0005.swift":{"type":"file","identifier":"01-01-01-code-0005.swift","content":["import StatoscopeTesting","","final class CounterTest: XCTestCase {","","    func testUserFlow() throws {","        try Counter.GIVEN {","            Counter()","        }","        .THEN(\\.viewDisplaysTotalCount, equals: 0)","        .WHEN(.userTappedIncrementButton)","        .THEN(\\.viewDisplaysTotalCount, equals: 1)","        .WHEN(.userTappedDecrementButton)","        .THEN(\\.viewDisplaysTotalCount, equals: 0)","        .WHEN(.userTappedDecrementButton)","        .THEN(\\.viewDisplaysTotalCount, equals: 0)","        .runTest()","    }","","}"],"fileType":"swift","syntax":"swift","fileName":"CounterTests.swift","highlights":[]},"01-01-01-code-0003.swift":{"fileName":"Counter.swift","type":"file","syntax":"swift","identifier":"01-01-01-code-0003.swift","fileType":"swift","highlights":[{"line":6},{"line":7},{"line":8},{"line":9},{"line":10}],"content":["import Statoscope","","private final class Counter: Scope {","","    var viewDisplaysTotalCount: Int = 0","","    enum When {","        case userTappedIncrementButton","        case userTappedDecrementButton","    }","}"]},"01-01-01-code-0004.swift":{"fileType":"swift","content":["import Statoscope","","private final class Counter: Scope {","","    var viewDisplaysTotalCount: Int = 0","","    enum When {","        case userTappedIncrementButton","        case userTappedDecrementButton","    }","","    func update(_ when: When) throws {","        \/\/ TODO","    }","}"],"identifier":"01-01-01-code-0004.swift","type":"file","highlights":[],"fileName":"Counter.swift","syntax":"swift"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-04-Injection":{"title":"Dependency Injection","estimatedTime":"30min","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn how to easily design dependencies and inject them into your scopes. Dependency injection simplifies the structure of your code by externalizing the management of dependencies, making your code more modular, testable, and flexible. In this tutorial, we will demonstrate dependency injection using an example of a simple news feed application."}],"kind":"project","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-04-Injection","type":"topic","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-04-injection","role":"project"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects#What-is-a-side-effect":{"title":"What is a side effect?","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Trigger effects that will get back to your scope as a new When event."}],"kind":"section","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects#What-is-a-side-effect","type":"section","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-02-statewhenandeffects#What-is-a-side-effect","role":"pseudoSymbol"}}}